1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Bb4+ 4. Bd2 Qe7 5. g3 Nc6 6. Bg2 Bxd2+ 7. Nbxd2 d6 8.
O-O e5 9. d5 Nb8 10. e4 a5 {Black makes this move before 0-0, but it will all
transpose sooner or later.} 11. Ne1 O-O 12. Nd3 Na6 {We are back on track.} 13.
a3 Bg4 $1 {I like this move and recommend it wholeheartedly. As we know that
Qc2 will be met with Be2 and Qe1 is not so comfortable, that leaves only the
option of f3 - which reduces the options of the g2 bishop even further.} 14. f3
Bd7 15. b4 c6 (15... axb4 16. axb4 c6 17. Qb3 cxd5 18. cxd5 Nc7 {Is a better
way to reach the same position as in the game. As it turns out, not taking on
b4 gives White the additional option of taking on a5.}) 16. Qb3 (16. bxa5 $14 {
After this move, White holds a small edge.}) 16... cxd5 17. cxd5 (17. exd5 {
Would have been possible, but it can be met with an undermining move...} axb4
18. axb4 b5 $1 {And here we see the benefit of provoking f3. The bishop on g2
could have been a dangerous piece, but now it's just as if its fire-breathing
mouth has been clamped down!} 19. f4 (19. cxb5 Bxb5 $15) 19... e4 20. Rfe1 e3 {
Black is having all the fun here!}) 17... axb4 18. axb4 Nc7 $1 {This is a very
typical idea. Black wants to transfer his knight from b5-d4 - everything just
works like clockwork from here.} 19. Qb2 (19. Nc4 Nb5 20. Nb6 Nd4 21. Qb2 Rxa1
22. Rxa1 Bb5 $17 {Is just a total disaster for White, as all of Black's pieces
are tremendously charged up.}) 19... Bb5 $1 {The difference between the
activity of the two bishops can be apparent even to a beginner here!} (19...
Nb5 {With the idea of Nd4 followed by Bb5 was also an interesting thought.})
20. Ra3 Rxa3 21. Qxa3 Ba6 $1 (21... Bxd3 {It's true that this exchange is
always beneficial for Black; but the point is that here we aren't fighting for
the c5 square as it well covered and our bishop is too active as of now just
to give it up - hence it makes sense to play Ba6.} 22. Qxd3 $14) 22. Rc1 Nb5
23. Qa5 Nd4 {The d3 knight is attacked and our own knight is perhaps one of
the strongest ones in the history of chess!} 24. Bf1 (24. Rc7 Qd8 25. Nc1 Nd7 {
Threatening b6} 26. Rc3 Qg5 $17 {Lo and behold, the queen joins the party!})
24... Nh5 {Making way for the queen to go to g5.} 25. Nf2 Be2 (25... Qg5 {
Would have been just terminal.} 26. b5 Bxb5 27. Bxb5 Qxd2 $1 {a nice little
tactic} 28. Qxd2 Nxf3+ 29. Kg2 Nxd2 $19 {With two pawns up, this is just
mopping up now.}) 26. Rc3 Qg5 27. Qa2 {The bishop is playing, so is the queen
and the knights; if someone isn't yet in the party, it's the rook - and after
the next move he promptly gets an invitation!} f5 $1 28. exf5 Qxf5 29. Bg2 Nf6
30. Rc7 Bxf3 31. Rxb7 Ng4 32. Nxg4 Bxg4 33. Nf1 Ne2+ 34. Kh1 Bf3 35. Nd2 Nxg3+
{Beliavsky's play was precise and beautiful! A game from which we learn tons
and tons of stuff.} 0-1

