{This game is absolutely top-level chess for the Bogo Indian. In today's chess
world, both White and Black are known as legends, and it is a treat to watch
them fight in the Bogo Indian.} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Bb4+ 4. Bd2 Qe7 5. g3
Nc6 6. Bg2 Bxd2+ 7. Nbxd2 (7. Qxd2 $2 Ne4 8. Qc2 Qb4+ 9. Nc3 Nxc3 10. Qxc3
Qxc3+ 11. bxc3 d6 12. Nd2 Na5 $15) 7... d6 8. O-O (8. Nf1 {Is a move that you
must be aware of, because the knight can come to e3. But it's one thing to be
aware and quite another to be afraid. This move is hardly terrifying and Black
can just continue with his normal play.} O-O 9. Ne3 e5 10. O-O Re8 {Keeping
pressure on e2 so that Nd5 is not so easy to execute.} 11. d5 Nb8 {When I am
not so sure what the knight is doing on e3, we just continue with our normal
plan of a5 and Na6.}) 8... O-O (8... a5) 9. e4 e5 10. d5 Nb8 11. Ne1 a5 12. Nd3
Na6 13. a3 Bg4 $1 {Inserting this move is in our interest.} 14. f3 Bd7 15. b4
axb4 {Jussupow improves on Beliavsky's play though Beliavsky's game was played
three years after this!!} (15... c6 16. bxa5 $14) 16. axb4 c6 17. dxc6 (17. Qb3
cxd5 18. cxd5 Nc7 {Would take us back to Skembris-Beliavsky.}) 17... bxc6 18.
Qc2 (18. Qb3 $5 $14 {Is also a possibility: it makes sense to reroute the
knight to d4 via e6 from c7 - so Nc7.} Nc7 19. Qc3 {With the idea of putting
pressure on e5 with c5. Now I quite like Tony Kosten's idea of probing White's
king side with h5} h5 $5 20. c5 Nb5 21. Qb2 dxc5 22. Nxc5 Be6 (22... Nd4 23.
Nc4 $16) 23. Qxe5 Nd7 24. Nxd7 Qxd7 {Where the position is fine for Black.
This variation was just to give you an idea of how play could continue.}) 18...
d5 $5 {Yusupov doesn't sit still and lashes out in the centre; it could have
been possible to continue calmly with Nc7-e6-d4 ideas.} (18... Nc7) 19. c5 $6 (
19. Qc3 $5 {Was a more prudent way to play; White will retain some advantage
here.}) (19. b5 $6 Nb4 20. Nxb4 Qxb4 21. bxc6 Qc5+ 22. Kh1 Bxc6 $15) 19... Be6
$6 (19... dxe4 {Was also a very good move.} 20. fxe4 (20. Nxe4 Nd5 21. Qd2 Bf5
$11) 20... Ng4 21. Nc4 $2 Nxb4 $19 {Is quite a nice variation.}) 20. Ra4 $1 {
Defending b4 and creating a threat against the e5 pawn.} dxe4 21. fxe4 (21.
Nxe4 Nxe4 22. fxe4 Qb7 $11) 21... Ng4 $1 {Defends e5 and threatens Ne3.} 22.
Rfa1 Nc7 23. Rxa8 Nxa8 $1 {This is definitely the best move of the game, one
that you can learn a lot from. White is better on the queen side and hence
Black doesn't exchange both the rooks, as then he would be devoid of
counterplay. He keeps one of the rooks, so that later he can break with f5 and
create counterplay in this position.} (23... Rxa8 $2 24. Rxa8+ Nxa8 25. Qa4 $16
) 24. Nf3 (24. Nc4 Bxc4 25. Qxc4 Qg5 $132) 24... f6 25. Qc1 $2 (25. h3 Ne3 26.
Qa4 $1 Rc8 $1 $15 {Black holds a good edge - because he has covered all his
weaknesses and can now start attacking White's.}) 25... Nc7 {Improving the
worst placed piece.} 26. Bf1 $6 {Trying to stop Nb5-d4 but is now met with an
energetic break in the centre.} f5 $1 27. Qg5 (27. Nfxe5 fxe4 28. Nxg4 exd3 $17
) (27. Ndxe5 fxe4 28. Nxg4 exf3 $17) 27... Qd7 {Black retains the queens and
gets ready to come into the weaknesses in White's position.} 28. Ra7 $2 (28.
Rd1 fxe4 29. Nf2 Nd5 $17) 28... h6 (28... fxe4 $1 29. Ndxe5 (29. Nfxe5 Nxe5 30.
Qxe5 Rxf1+ 31. Kxf1 Qxd3+ $19) 29... Nxe5 30. Qxe5 exf3 31. Rxc7 f2+ $19) 29.
Qg6 (29. Qd2 fxe4 30. Ndxe5 Nxe5 31. Qxd7 Nxf3+ $19) 29... Rf6 {The queen is
lost.} 30. Rxc7 (30. Qh5 fxe4 $19) 30... Qxc7 31. Qe8+ Kh7 $19 32. exf5 (32.
Qh5 $142) 32... Bf7 $1 33. Qa8 e4 34. Bh3 Ne3 {This game has illustrated the
fighting nature of the Bogo Indian. It shows that the play is not always on
the queen side. You must be prepared to shift gears - just like how Yusupov
did - and start a king side initiative as well!} 0-1

