1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. g3 Bb4+ 4. Bd2 Qe7 5. Bg2 Nc6 6. Nf3 Bxd2+ 7. Nbxd2 d6 8.
O-O O-O 9. e4 e5 10. d5 Nb8 11. b4 {Ne1-d3 is considered the main plan in such
positions, but b4 must not be underestimated! The main advantage of this move
is the speed that it is providing to White's play on the queen side. White
wastes no time with his queen side expansion.} a5 {As is usual, we continue
with our normal development.} 12. a3 Na6 13. Qb3 {The queen comes to an
aggressive post; it's now Black's turn to come up with something and I think
it is the right time to break into the centre.} c6 (13... Bg4 {Is another
perfectly playable alternative for less forcing play.}) 14. dxc6 {I think this
capture is always critical, as it changes the flow of play. While permitting
cd5 allows Black to gain good play whichever way White recaptures, after dc6
the structure is totally changed and Black will have to be very careful not to
land in an inferior position.} bxc6 15. Qc3 (15. c5 {As mentioned in the
theory file, this seems like the critical try in this position.} Be6 16. cxd6 (
16. Qc3 axb4 17. axb4 dxc5 18. bxc5 Nd7 19. Nxe5 Nxe5 20. Qxe5 Nxc5 $11) 16...
Qxd6 17. Nc4 Bxc4 18. Qxc4 axb4 19. axb4 Nxb4 20. Rad1 Qe7 21. Nxe5 Qxe5 22.
Qxb4 {What can I say about this position? I think the best White can get out
of this is 4 v 3 on the same side. It will be a tough defence for Black but I
think he can hold the position.}) 15... Bg4 16. Nh4 Rfb8 (16... g6 {Was a
simple move, keeping the knight out of f5.}) 17. Rfb1 Nc7 (17... axb4 18. axb4
g6 {Was another way to play.}) 18. h3 Bd7 (18... axb4 {It would have made
sense to insert this move.}) 19. bxa5 {White wins a pawn and is clearly better
- but that's where the Bogo Indian's strengths come in. Black has all his
pieces well placed and a good pawn structure. Hence, even though he is a pawn
down, he has lots of fighting chances.} g6 20. Rb6 $6 (20. Rxb8+ Rxb8 21. Rb1 {
Was a good way to continue.}) 20... Ne6 {The knight is coming into d4 - Black
is already ok!} 21. Rab1 Rd8 22. Nb3 c5 23. a6 Bc8 {Once the a6 pawn falls,
White will be worse off as his pawn structure would be weak and there are lots
of holes in his position; moreover, the a6 pawn cannot be defended, hence
Black has the advantage now.} 24. Qa5 Nd7 25. Nd2 Nxb6 26. Rxb6 Nc7 27. a7 Ne6
28. Rb8 Rxa7 29. Qc3 Nd4 30. Kh2 Be6 31. Rxd8+ Qxd8 32. Nhf3 Qa8 33. Nxd4 cxd4
34. Qb4 Ra6 35. Bf1 Kg7 36. c5 dxc5 37. Qxc5 Ra5 38. Bb5 f6 39. a4 Ra7 40. f4
exf4 41. gxf4 Qb8 42. Kg2 Rf7 43. f5 Qf4 44. Qxd4 gxf5 45. Qf2 Qxf2+ 46. Kxf2
fxe4 47. Nxe4 Bxh3 48. a5 Ra7 49. a6 Bc8 50. Nc5 Rc7 51. Na4 Bd7 52. Bxd7 Rxd7
53. Nc5 Ra7 54. Ke3 h5 0-1

