1. d4 e6 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. c4 Bb4+ 4. Bd2 Qe7 5. g3 Nc6 6. Bg2 Bxd2+ 7. Nbxd2 d6 8.
O-O a5 9. e4 e5 10. d5 Nb8 11. Ne1 O-O 12. Nd3 Bg4 $5 {Just to indulge you
through an idea that you can try some day, I would like to suggest this move
before Na6. So are there any benefits to be derived from this move order or is
it just transpositional in nature? As we shall see, there are benefits.} 13. f3
Bd7 14. f4 {This is the main way to continue. I am not so sure if the king
side attack will be successful, just because we have Bd7 instead of Na6, but
White figures out that if the plan with a3 is not so good then I might as well
try for a king side attack. Imagine your opponent having read in some opening
manual that queen side expansion is the best plan against the Bogo Indian and
so he plays this move. You can really give him a jolt now with...} (14. a3 a4
$1 {A move that would have been impossible if, instead of Bd7, we had played
Na6.}) 14... Na6 (14... c6 {Is usually the automatic reaction to a king side
offensive with f4. But here it's not so good, as White has a powerful move in..
.} 15. c5 $1 cxd5 16. fxe5 dxe5 17. exd5 Bb5 18. Qb3 Bxd3 19. d6 $1 Qe6 20.
Qxd3 $16 {With White extremely better.}) 15. f5 {White goes ahead with the aim
of steamrolling Black on the king side; but, as seen in Mamedjarova-Naiditsch,
this just places another pawn on a light square.} h6 $1 {Black takes
precautions on the king side before starting the queen side play.} 16. g4 Nh7 {
Now to get in g5 will take a long time, and Black can start his queen side
counterplay.} 17. Nf3 c6 $1 {As is usual!} 18. h4 {With the centre under
pressure, it isn't wise to play so riskily!} cxd5 19. cxd5 {The c4 pawn moves
and you know that d7 B is jumping in its chair!} (19. exd5 Qd8 {With the idea
of e4.} (19... e4 20. Re1) 20. Qe2 Re8 $15 {b5 will come up soon!}) 19... Bb5 {
Threatening Nc5.} 20. Rf2 Rfc8 {Black's pieces somehow seem more coherent to
me.} 21. Rc1 $2 {But the position wasn't so easy anyway.} Rxc1 22. Nxc1 (22.
Qxc1 Bxd3 $19) 22... Nc5 $19 23. Qe1 Bd3 $1 {Something has to give way now.}
24. Nh2 Qxh4 {This is exactly what happens - White tries to push pawns on the
king side in anticipation that he will get an attack; but after the Black
counterattacks on the other flank, these same pawns on the king side fall off
like ripe fruit.} 25. Re2 Qxe1+ 26. Rxe1 Rc8 27. Re3 Bxe4 28. Bxe4 Nxe4 29. Nb3
Nhf6 30. Re2 a4 31. Na5 Rc1+ 32. Kg2 Nc5 {Great game by Ulibin, showing us
once again how to meet f4-f5 with queen side counterplay.} 0-1

