{Even though this is a rapid game, the fact that the great Ivanchuk decided to
try this line gives us a huge boost. It has to be good if Ivanchuk could beat
a 2660 player with it!} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Bb4+ 4. Bd2 Qe7 5. g3 Nc6 6.
Nc3 O-O 7. Bg2 Na5 8. b3 b6 9. Ne5 Bb7 10. Bxb7 Nxb7 11. O-O c5 $1 {This is
the correct undermining move in this position. Later we will put our rook on
c8 and maybe execute d5. But starting with c5 makes a lot of sense.} 12. a3 Ba5
$1 {I like this move by Ivanchuk - he keeps the bishop alive.} (12... Bxc3 13.
Bxc3 Rac8 {Is another way to equalise.}) 13. e3 Rfc8 $1 {Tremendous intuition
is required to make a move like this. The main reason why this rook is chosen
is to avoid weakening the a7 pawn.} (13... Rac8 $6 {Looks natural but is met
with...} 14. b4 $1 cxb4 15. axb4 Bxb4 (15... Qxb4 16. c5 $1 {Black queen's
path to safety has been blocked and White is better with moves like Rb1 or Ne4
coming up.}) 16. Rxa7 d6 17. Nd5 $1 exd5 (17... Nxd5 18. cxd5 Bxd2 19. Nc6 $1)
18. Bxb4 $14 {White keeps a small advantage! These variations must surely have
flashed into the mind of Great Chucky.}) 14. Qf3 (14. dxc5 Bxc3 15. Bxc3 Nxc5
$11 {With good control over the e4 square; and b3 pawn being a little soft,
Black is totally fine.}) 14... Nd8 {Black's idea is to play d6 and push the
knight on e5 away. It's quite surprising that Ivanchuk didn't go in for the
